    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nFor callbacks of functions like `Iter:find()`, `Iter:filter()`, (~~future?: `Iter:reduce()`~~  `Iter:fold()`), it's useful to know\r\n\r\n1. the \"previous\" element\r\n2. the result of the previous callback\r\n\r\nThis allows the callback to compare / reason about observed elements and results.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nUsing [javascript's reduce()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/reduce#parameters) as inspiration, we could pass these args:\r\n\r\n- `i`: current index\r\n- `prev_val`: previous value (maybe not needed because of `i` ?)\r\n- `result` (or `accum`?): Result of the previous callback. On first call, `initial_val` if specified, otherwise the first value of the iterator (`iter[1]`).",
    "closed_at": "2024-04-30T11:30:23Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Usually reduce just takes a function with two elements, e.g. [scala's reduce](https://www.scala-lang.org/api/2.13.3/scala/collection/immutable/List.html).\r\n\r\nIf you need more state then it's better IMO to just run an intermediate `map()`.",
