            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Repeating my comment [here](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/27021#issuecomment-1893875635):\r\n\r\n> For callbacks of functions like Iter:find(), Iter:filter(), (future?: Iter:reduce()), it's useful to know\r\n> \r\n> - the \"previous\" element\r\n> - the result of the previous callback\r\n\r\nCan this not already be achieved with the API that we have? I don't want to pass a bunch of state to every stage of the iterator pipeline if it's not needed. It complicates the API and makes things more cumbersome/verbose/confusing. Instead if these things are needed the iterator itself should be able to support it.\r\n\r\n> Using [javascript's reduce()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/reduce#parameters) as inspiration, we could pass these args:\r\n> \r\n> * `i`: current index\r\n> * `prev_val`: previous value (maybe not needed because of i ?)\r\n> * `result` (or accum?): Result of the previous callback. On first call, initial_val if specified, otherwise the first value of the iterator (iter[1]).\r\n\r\nWe already support this:\r\n\r\n- Current index can be injected into the iterator pipeline with `:enumerate()`\r\n- `prev_val` and `result` are already supported by `:fold()`. The \"accumulator\" in `fold` can be _anything_, including a state table:\r\n\r\n  ```lua\r\n  local t = vim.iter({ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 }):fold({}, function(acc, v)\r\n    local last = acc.last or 0\r\n    acc.last = v\r\n    if not acc.result then\r\n      acc.result = 0\r\n    end\r\n    acc.result = acc.result + last + v\r\n    return acc\r\n  end)\r\n  vim.print(t.result)\r\n  -- 25\r\n  ```",
